#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:1
msgid "Feature Name: `crate-attr`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:2
msgid "Start Date: 2025-03-16"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:3
msgid ""
"RFC PR: [rust-lang/rfcs#3791](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/3791)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:4
msgid ""
"Rust Issue: [rust-lang/rust#138287](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/138287)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:9
msgid ""
"`--crate-attr` allows injecting crate-level attributes via the command line. "
"It is supported by all the official rustc drivers: Rustc, Rustdoc, Clippy, "
"Miri, and Rustfmt. Rustdoc extends it to doctests, discussed in further "
"detail below. It is encouraged, but not required, that external "
"`rustc_driver` tools also support this flag."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:14
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:17
msgid "There are three main motivations."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:19
msgid "CLI flags are easier to configure for a whole workspace at once."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:20
msgid ""
"When designing new features, we do not need to choose between attributes and "
"flags; adding an attribute automatically makes it possible to set with a "
"flag."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:21
msgid ""
"Tools that require a specific attribute can pass that attribute "
"automatically."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:23
msgid ""
"Each of these corresponds to a different set of stakeholders. The first "
"corresponds to developers writing Rust code. For this group, as the size of "
"their code increases and they split it into multiple crates, it becomes more "
"and more difficult to configure attributes for the whole workspace; they "
"need to be duplicated into the root of each crate. Some attributes that "
"could be useful to configure workspace-wide:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:24
msgid "`no_std`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:25
msgid ""
"`feature` (in particular, enabling unstable lints for a whole workspace at "
"once)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:26
msgid ""
"[`doc(html_{favicon,logo,playground,root}_url}`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"rustdoc/write-documentation/the-doc-attribute.html#at-the-crate-level)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:27
msgid "[`doc(html_no_source)`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/75497)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:28
msgid "`doc(attr(...))`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:30
msgid ""
"Cargo has features for configuring flags for a workspace (RUSTFLAGS, `target."
"<name>.rustflags`, `profile.<name>.rustflags`), but no such mechanism exists "
"for crate-level attributes."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:32
msgid ""
"Additionally, some existing CLI options could have been useful as "
"attributes. This leads to the second group: Maintainers of the Rust "
"language. Often we need to decide between attributes and flags; either we "
"duplicate features between the two (lints, `crate-name`, `crate-type`), or "
"we make it harder to configure the options for stakeholder group 1."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:34
msgid ""
"The third group is the authors of external tools. The [original motivation]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/52355) for this feature was for "
"Crater, which wanted to enable a rustfix feature in _all_ crates it built "
"without having to modify the source code. Other motivations include the "
"currently-unstable [`register-tool`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/66079#issuecomment-1010266282), which with this RFC could be an "
"attribute passed by the external tool (or configured in the workspace), and "
"[build-std](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/"
"pull/3791#discussion_r1998684847), which wants to inject `no_std` into all "
"crates being compiled."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:42
msgid "Guide-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:45
msgid ""
"The `--crate-attr` flag allows you to inject attributes into the crate root. "
"For example, `--crate-attr=crate_name=\"test\"` acts as if `#!"
"[crate_name=\"test\"]` were present before the first source line of the "
"crate root."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:48
msgid "To inject multiple attributes, pass `--crate-attr` multiple times."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:50
msgid ""
"This feature lets you pass attributes to your whole workspace at once, even "
"if rustc doesn't natively support them as flags. For example, you could "
"configure `strict_provenance_lints` for all your crates by adding `build."
"rustflags = [\"--crate-attr=feature(strict_provenance_lints)\", \"-"
"Wfuzzy_provenance_casts\", \"-Wlossy_provenance_casts\"]` to `.cargo/config."
"toml`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:55
msgid ""
"This feature also applies to doctests. Running (for example) "
"`RUSTDOCFLAGS=\"--crate-attr='feature(strict_provenance_lints)' -"
"Wfuzzy_provenance_casts\" cargo test --doc` will enable "
"`fuzzy_provenance_casts` for all doctests that are run."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:58
msgid ""
"(This snippet is adapted from [the unstable book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"nightly/unstable-book/compiler-flags/crate-attr.html#crate-attr).)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:62
msgid "Reference-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:65
msgid "Semantics"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:67
msgid "Any crate-level attribute is valid to pass to `--crate-attr`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:69
msgid "Formally, the expansion behaves as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:71
msgid ""
"The crate root (initial file given to rustc) is parsed as if `--crate-attr` "
"were not present."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:72
msgid "The attributes in `--crate-attr` are parsed."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:73
msgid ""
"The attributes are injected at the top of the crate root (see below for "
"relative ordering to any existing attributes)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:75
msgid "Compilation continues as normal."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:77
msgid ""
"As a consequence, this feature does not affect [shebang parsing](https://doc."
"rust-lang.org/nightly/reference/input-format.html#shebang-removal), nor can "
"it affect nor be affected by comments that appear on the first source line."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:79
msgid ""
"Another consequence is that the argument to `--crate-attr` is syntactically "
"isolated from the rest of the crate; `--crate-attr=/*` is always an error "
"and cannot begin a multi-line comment."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:81
msgid ""
"`--crate-attr` is treated as Rust source code, which means that whitespace, "
"block comments, and raw strings are valid: `'--crate-attr= crate_name /*foo "
"bar*/ = r#\"my-crate\"# '` is equivalent to `--crate-attr=crate_name=\"my-"
"crate\"`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:83
msgid ""
"The argument to `--crate-attr` is treated as-if it were surrounded by `#!"
"[ ]`, i.e. it must be an inner attribute and it cannot include multiple "
"attributes, nor can it be any grammar production other than an [`Attr`]"
"(https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/reference/attributes.html). In "
"particular, this implies that `//!` syntax for doc-comments is disallowed "
"(although `doc = \"...\"` is fine)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:86
msgid ""
"If the attribute is already present in the source code, it behaves exactly "
"as it would if duplicated twice in the source. For example, duplicating "
"`no_std` is idempotent; duplicating `crate_type` generates both types; and "
"duplicating `crate_name` is idempotent if the names are the same and a hard "
"error otherwise. It is suggested, but not required, that the implementation "
"not warn on idempotent attributes, even if it would normally warn that "
"duplicate attributes are unused."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:90
msgid ""
"The compiler is free to re-order steps 1 and 2 in the above order if "
"desirable. This shouldn't have any user-observable effect beyond changes in "
"diagnostics."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:93
msgid "Doctests"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:95
msgid ""
"`--crate-attr` is also a rustdoc flag. Rustdoc behaves identically to rustc "
"for the main crate being compiled. For doctests, by default, `--crate-attr` "
"applies to both the main crate and the generated doctest. This can be "
"overridden for the doctest using `--crate-attr=doc(test(attr(...)))`. `--"
"crate-attr=doc(...)` attributes never apply to the generated doctest, only "
"to the main crate (with the exception of `doc(test(attr(...)))`, which "
"applies the inner `...` attribute, not the doc attribute itself)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:103
msgid "Ordering"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:105
msgid ""
"Attributes are applied in the order they were given on the command line; so "
"`--crate-attr=warn(unused) --crate-attr=deny(unused)` is equivalent to "
"`deny(unused)`. `crate-attr` attributes are applied before source code "
"attributes. For example, the following file, when compiled with `crate-"
"attr=deny(unused)`, does not fail with an error, but only warns:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:114
msgid ""
"Additionally, all existing `-A -W -D -F` flags become aliases for `--crate-"
"attr` (`allow`, `warn`, `deny`, and `forbid`, respectively). In particular, "
"this implies that the following CLI flag combinations are exactly equivalent:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:115
msgid "`-D unused`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:116
msgid "`-A unused -D unused`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:117
msgid "`--crate-attr=allow(unused) -D unused`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:119
msgid ""
"`--force-warn` has no attribute that is equivalent, and is not affected by "
"this RFC."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:121
msgid ""
"\"Equivalence\" as described in this section only makes sense because lint "
"attributes are defined to have a precedence order. Other attributes, such as "
"doc-comments, define no such precedence. Those attributes have whatever "
"meaning they define for their order. For example, passing `'--crate-attr=doc "
"= \"Compiled on March 18 2025\"'` to a crate with `#![doc = \"My awesome "
"crate\"]` on the first line would generate documentation for the crate root "
"reading:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:129
msgid "Spans, modules, and editions"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:131
msgid ""
"`include!`, `include_str!`, and `module_path!` all behave the same as when "
"written in source code at the top of the crate root. That is, any module or "
"path-relative resolution within the `--crate-attr` attribute should be "
"treated the same as ocurring within the crate root."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:136
msgid ""
"`--crate-attr` shares an edition with the crate (i.e. it is affected by `--"
"edition`). This may be observable because `doc` attributes can invoke "
"arbitrary macros. Consider this use of [indoc](https://docs.rs/indoc/latest/"
"indoc/):"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:137
msgid ""
"```\n"
"--crate-attr='doc = indoc::indoc! {\"\n"
"    test\n"
"    this\n"
"\"}'\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:143
msgid ""
"Edition-related changes to how proc-macros are passed tokens may need to "
"consider how crate-attr is affected."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:145
msgid ""
"`file!`, `line!`, `column!` _within_ the --crate-attr attribute use a "
"synthetic file (e.g., file might be `<cli-arg>`). This avoids ambiguity for "
"the span overlapping actual bytes in any existing files on disk, and matches "
"precedent in other toolchains, e.g., see clang's output for `--include` on "
"the command line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:151
msgid ""
"```````shell\n"
"$ touch t.h\n"
"$ clang t.h --include foo.h\n"
"<built-in>:1:10: fatal error: 'foo.h' file not found\n"
"    1 | #include \"foo.h\"\n"
"      |          ^~~~~~~\n"
"1 error generated.\n"
"```````"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:160
msgid ""
"The line and column will ideally be relative to the individual --crate-attr "
"command line flag, though this is considered a best-effort detail for "
"quality of diagnostics.  They will not be affected by the injected `#![` "
"surrounding the parsed attribute."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:166
msgid ""
"The original source parsing (i.e., the file provided to rustc) is not "
"affected by the injected attributes, in effect, they are treated as ocurring "
"within 0 bytes at the start of the file."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:172
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:175
msgid ""
"It makes it harder for Rust developers to know whether it's idiomatic to use "
"flags or attributes. In practice, this has not be a large drawback for "
"`crate_name` and `crate_type`, although for lints perhaps a little more so "
"since they were only recently stabilized in Cargo."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:178
msgid ""
"Using this feature can make code in a crate dependent on attributes provided "
"through the build system, such that the code doesn't build if reorganized or "
"copied to another project."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:180
msgid "Rationale and alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:183
msgid ""
"We could require `--crate-attr=#![foo]` instead. This is more verbose and "
"requires extensive shell quoting, for not much benefit. It does however "
"resolve the concern around `column!` (to include the `#![` in the column "
"number), and looks closer to the syntax in a source file."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:184
msgid ""
"We could disallow comments in the attribute. This perhaps makes the design "
"less surprising, but complicates the implementation for little benefit."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:185
msgid ""
"We could apply `--crate-attr` after attributes in the source, instead of "
"before. This has two drawbacks:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:186
msgid ""
"It has different behavior for lints than the existing A/W/D flags, so those "
"flags could not semantically be unified with crate-attr. We would be adding "
"yet another precedence group."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:187
msgid ""
"It does not allow configuring a \"default\" option for a workspace and then "
"overriding it in a single crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:188
msgid ""
"We could add a syntax for passing multiple attributes in a single CLI flag. "
"We would have to find a syntax that avoids ambiguity _and_ that does not mis-"
"parse the data inside string literals (i.e. picking a fixed string, such as "
"`|`, would not work because it has to take quote nesting into account). This "
"greatly complicates the implementation for little benefit. We also already "
"have @file syntax to pass in arguments from a file which provides an escape "
"hatch if this is truly helpful."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:190
msgid ""
"This cannot be done in a library or macro. It can be done in an external "
"tool, but only by modifying the source in place, which requires first "
"parsing it, and in general is much more brittle than this approach (for "
"example, preventing the argument from injecting a unterminated block "
"comment, or from injecting a non-attribute grammar production, becomes much "
"harder)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:192
msgid ""
"In the author's opinion, having source injected via this mechanism does not "
"make code any harder to read than the existing flags that are already stable "
"(in particular `-C panic` and `--edition` come to mind)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:194
msgid "Prior art"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:197
msgid ""
"HTML allows `<meta http-equiv=...>` to emulate headers, which is very useful "
"for using hosted infra where one does not control the server."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:198
msgid ""
"bash allows `-x` and similar to emulate `set -x` (for all `set` arguments). "
"It also allows `-O shopt_...` for all `shopt ...` arguments."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:199
msgid ""
"tmux config syntax is the same as its CLI syntax (for example `tmux set-"
"option ...` is mostly the same as writing `set-option ...` in `tmux.conf`, "
"modulo some issues around startup order and inherited options)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:201
msgid "Unresolved questions"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:204
msgid ""
"Is `--crate-name` equivalent to `--crate-attr=crate_name`? As currently "
"implemented, the answer is no. Fixing this is hard; see https://github.com/"
"rust-lang/rust/issues/91632 and https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"pull/108221#issuecomment-1435765434 (these do not directly answer why, but I "
"am not aware of any documentation that does)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:206
msgid "Future possibilities"
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:209
msgid ""
"This proposal would make it easier to use external tools with [`#!"
"[register_tool]`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/66079#issuecomment-1010266282), since they could be configured for a "
"whole workspace at once instead of individually; and could be configured "
"without modifying the source code."
msgstr ""

#: src/3791-crate-attr.md:211
msgid ""
"We may want to allow [procedural macros at the crate root](https://github."
"com/rust-lang/rust/issues/54726). At that point we have to decide whether "
"those macros can see `--crate-attr`. I _think_ this should not be an issue "
"because the attributes are prepended, not appended, but it needs more "
"research."
msgstr ""
